======================================================================
SECTION 8: FLAT SPECTRUM AND H — BEYOND CIRCULANTS
======================================================================

At n=7: ALL 240 H-maximizers are isomorphic to Paley T_7.
This means Paley is the UNIQUE (up to isomorphism) H-maximizer.
And T_7 has the flattest spectrum among circulants.

Question: does T_7 also have the flattest spectrum among ALL
tournaments on 7 vertices? (Non-circulant tournaments have
non-circulant eigenvalue structure.)

For non-circulant tournaments, A is NOT normal, so eigenvalues
can be complex with non-trivial Jordan blocks.

The SINGULAR VALUES of A (not eigenvalues) determine ||A||_F,
and for normal matrices, singular values = |eigenvalues|.

For regular tournaments: A has constant row sums = (n-1)/2.
  Largest eigenvalue = (n-1)/2 (Perron root).
  Sum of |eigenvalue|^2 = tr(A^T A) = sum A[i][j]^2 = n(n-1)/2.
  So mean |λ|^2 = n(n-1)/(2n) = (n-1)/2.

For T_7 (circulant): |λ_0|=3, |λ_k|=√2 for k=1,...,6
  Check: 9 + 6*2 = 21 = 7*6/2 ✓

Conjecture: Among all regular tournaments on n vertices,
  the H-maximizer has the flattest SINGULAR VALUE spectrum.

This is a MUCH stronger conjecture than the circulant version.

======================================================================
SECTION 9: GENERATING FUNCTION FOR H OF CIRCULANT
======================================================================

For circulant tournament on Z_p with connection set S:
  A = Σ_{s∈S} P^s where P = cyclic shift matrix
  Eigenvalues of P: ω^k (k=0,...,p-1)
  Eigenvalues of A: f(ω^k) = Σ_{s∈S} ω^{ks}

H(T) = # Hamiltonian paths. For a CIRCULANT:
  Each HP orbit under Z_p has size p (p prime, no fixed points)
  So H = p * (# orbits) ≡ 0 (mod p)

  This is confirmed: H(T_7) = 189 = 7*27, H(T_11) = 95095 = 11*8645

  p = 7: all circulant H values mod p:
    All H ≡ 0 (mod 7) ✓

  p = 11: all circulant H values mod p:
    All H ≡ 0 (mod 11) ✓

H/p values (number of Z_p orbits of HPs):
